WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.470 align:middle line:90%
[THEME MUSIC]

00:00:01.470 --> 00:00:19.576 align:middle line:90%


00:00:19.576 --> 00:00:21.450 align:middle line:84%
>>GEORGE NOORY: Well,
welcome to this edition

00:00:21.450 --> 00:00:22.250 align:middle line:90%
of "Beyond Belief."

00:00:22.250 --> 00:00:23.730 align:middle line:10%
And we've got a
great show for you.

00:00:23.730 --> 00:00:27.930 align:middle line:10%
We've got two Jays talking
about "Hollywood Decoded,"

00:00:27.930 --> 00:00:33.120 align:middle line:10%
the ability for Hollywood to put
in symbolism in different kinds

00:00:33.120 --> 00:00:35.820 align:middle line:10%
of films and movies
to teach you a lesson,

00:00:35.820 --> 00:00:37.610 align:middle line:10%
to give you information.

00:00:37.610 --> 00:00:39.795 align:middle line:84%
Their program, of course,
is on the "Gaia" series,

00:00:39.795 --> 00:00:41.040 align:middle line:90%
"Hollywood Decoded."

00:00:41.040 --> 00:00:42.460 align:middle line:90%
I want you to take a look at it.

00:00:42.460 --> 00:00:44.334 align:middle line:10%
>>JAY DYER: In Ridley
Scott's "Blade Runner,"

00:00:44.334 --> 00:00:46.620 align:middle line:10%
we have the warning of a
completely synthetic future,

00:00:46.620 --> 00:00:49.740 align:middle line:10%
something that's completely
overwritten normal reality.

00:00:49.740 --> 00:00:53.167 align:middle line:84%
LA traffic is still
bad 20 years from now.

00:00:53.167 --> 00:00:54.000 align:middle line:90%
>>JAY WEIDNER: Yeah.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:57.390 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: Giant ziggurats
towering over the entire city

00:00:57.390 --> 00:01:00.210 align:middle line:84%
with one corporation that runs
it all, the Tyrell Corporation.

00:01:00.210 --> 00:01:01.710 align:middle line:90%
And what are they obsessed with?

00:01:01.710 --> 00:01:04.560 align:middle line:84%
Artificial intelligence
and human engineering.

00:01:04.560 --> 00:01:08.370 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: So this film is
really an amazing exploration

00:01:08.370 --> 00:01:14.340 align:middle line:84%
of what happens when an
artificial creature, Decker,

00:01:14.340 --> 00:01:18.810 align:middle line:84%
begins to realize that he is
beginning to become self-aware,

00:01:18.810 --> 00:01:20.140 align:middle line:90%
self-conscious.

00:01:20.140 --> 00:01:22.450 align:middle line:84%
I think that is actually
what the film is about,

00:01:22.450 --> 00:01:27.930 align:middle line:84%
is Decker's coming from
kind of the matrix of being

00:01:27.930 --> 00:01:29.730 align:middle line:90%
artificial intelligence.

00:01:29.730 --> 00:01:33.300 align:middle line:84%
And Batty initiating
him, and leading him

00:01:33.300 --> 00:01:36.910 align:middle line:84%
in to individuality,
which he achieves.

00:01:36.910 --> 00:01:39.200 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: So with our two
Jays, of course, Jay Dyer,

00:01:39.200 --> 00:01:42.070 align:middle line:10%
you are the author, Jay,
of "Esoteric Hollywood,"

00:01:42.070 --> 00:01:46.480 align:middle line:10%
which is an amazing book that
deals with the intricacies

00:01:46.480 --> 00:01:47.280 align:middle line:10%
of Hollywood.

00:01:47.280 --> 00:01:48.624 align:middle line:10%
How did you come up with that?

00:01:48.624 --> 00:01:50.790 align:middle line:10%
>>DYER: Well, it's born of
a love of film, actually.

00:01:50.790 --> 00:01:54.600 align:middle line:10%
I went to undergrad
and grad school

00:01:54.600 --> 00:01:56.790 align:middle line:10%
focused on film and philosophy.

00:01:56.790 --> 00:01:58.980 align:middle line:10%
And the more that you take
film classes, the more

00:01:58.980 --> 00:02:00.990 align:middle line:10%
you realize there's actually
interplay between these two

00:02:00.990 --> 00:02:01.790 align:middle line:10%
worlds.

00:02:01.790 --> 00:02:03.690 align:middle line:84%
And simultaneously
with that, I was also

00:02:03.690 --> 00:02:06.750 align:middle line:84%
studying conspiracy
on my own on the side.

00:02:06.750 --> 00:02:08.639 align:middle line:84%
I started realizing
that conspiracy is also

00:02:08.639 --> 00:02:10.070 align:middle line:90%
related to Hollywood as well.

00:02:10.070 --> 00:02:10.903 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Absolutely.

00:02:10.903 --> 00:02:13.440 align:middle line:10%
>>DYER: And so it all just
kind of flowered together

00:02:13.440 --> 00:02:16.800 align:middle line:10%
into this book, after
about eight or 10 years.

00:02:16.800 --> 00:02:22.170 align:middle line:10%
And I happened to meet Jay
Weidner at a conference.

00:02:22.170 --> 00:02:25.151 align:middle line:84%
And from that, we just decided
that this needed to be a show.

00:02:25.151 --> 00:02:26.400 align:middle line:90%
There's so much material here.

00:02:26.400 --> 00:02:29.700 align:middle line:84%
There's so many
metaphysical, secret society,

00:02:29.700 --> 00:02:32.100 align:middle line:84%
conspiracy topics that
relate to Hollywood.

00:02:32.100 --> 00:02:34.280 align:middle line:84%
And even the
blockbusters, that it

00:02:34.280 --> 00:02:37.287 align:middle line:84%
needs to be some kind of show
that demonstrates the symbolism

00:02:37.287 --> 00:02:38.370 align:middle line:90%
that you're talking about.

00:02:38.370 --> 00:02:39.703 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And a great show it is.

00:02:39.703 --> 00:02:42.380 align:middle line:84%
And of course, Jay Weidner,
that Jay Dyer just mentioned,

00:02:42.380 --> 00:02:46.440 align:middle line:84%
is a renowned filmmaker and
is responsible for developing

00:02:46.440 --> 00:02:49.260 align:middle line:84%
the "Beyond Belief" television
show five years ago.

00:02:49.260 --> 00:02:50.210 align:middle line:90%
Remember that day?

00:02:50.210 --> 00:02:50.790 align:middle line:90%
>>WEIDNER: I do.

00:02:50.790 --> 00:02:51.630 align:middle line:90%
It was a long time ago.

00:02:51.630 --> 00:02:52.588 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Well, welcome.

00:02:52.588 --> 00:02:55.080 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: It's been a long,
long road for "Beyond Belief."

00:02:55.080 --> 00:02:56.580 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It's been
a great road too.

00:02:56.580 --> 00:02:58.410 align:middle line:84%
Robert Frost once
said, "Two roads

00:02:58.410 --> 00:03:00.000 align:middle line:84%
diverged in the
yellow wood, and I

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:01.821 align:middle line:90%
took the one less traveled by."

00:03:01.821 --> 00:03:02.820 align:middle line:90%
That's what we did, Jay.

00:03:02.820 --> 00:03:04.110 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: That's
what we do, actually,

00:03:04.110 --> 00:03:05.460 align:middle line:90%
both you and I. It's our life.

00:03:05.460 --> 00:03:07.800 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: When you
met up with Jay Dyer

00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:09.510 align:middle line:84%
and started talking
about Hollywood

00:03:09.510 --> 00:03:11.590 align:middle line:84%
and all the strange
things that are going on,

00:03:11.590 --> 00:03:13.770 align:middle line:90%
what was it that you first saw?

00:03:13.770 --> 00:03:16.550 align:middle line:10%
>>WEIDNER: Well first,
like a companion.

00:03:16.550 --> 00:03:19.650 align:middle line:10%
I finally had someone I could
talk to about these things,

00:03:19.650 --> 00:03:23.760 align:middle line:10%
because it's been a
lonely road talking about,

00:03:23.760 --> 00:03:27.240 align:middle line:10%
saying that there are
esoteric symbols in the plots

00:03:27.240 --> 00:03:29.660 align:middle line:10%
of Hollywood films.

00:03:29.660 --> 00:03:32.700 align:middle line:84%
10 years ago, all I got
was raised eyebrows.

00:03:32.700 --> 00:03:34.290 align:middle line:10%
It was only in the
last few years,

00:03:34.290 --> 00:03:38.580 align:middle line:10%
probably because we're coming
at it from two different sides,

00:03:38.580 --> 00:03:40.350 align:middle line:10%
we've started actually
getting people

00:03:40.350 --> 00:03:43.500 align:middle line:10%
to understand that this
is really going on.

00:03:43.500 --> 00:03:45.570 align:middle line:10%
And then secondly, I
think filmmakers, in fact

00:03:45.570 --> 00:03:48.120 align:middle line:10%
I know filmmakers
like Christopher Nolan

00:03:48.120 --> 00:03:49.800 align:middle line:10%
are actually listening to us.

00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:52.235 align:middle line:10%
And they're starting to
slip things into their films

00:03:52.235 --> 00:03:53.610 align:middle line:10%
because they
realize that this is

00:03:53.610 --> 00:03:57.090 align:middle line:10%
what creates a lasting
benefit to the film,

00:03:57.090 --> 00:03:59.880 align:middle line:10%
that you can go watch
"2001: A Space Odyssey"

00:03:59.880 --> 00:04:02.640 align:middle line:10%
30 years after it
was made and still

00:04:02.640 --> 00:04:07.050 align:middle line:10%
find symbols and messages from
Stanley Kubrick in the film.

00:04:07.050 --> 00:04:08.670 align:middle line:84%
And they want that
kind of-- they

00:04:08.670 --> 00:04:11.620 align:middle line:84%
want their films to
last that long too.

00:04:11.620 --> 00:04:14.830 align:middle line:10%
And so I think that, like in
Interstellar for instance,

00:04:14.830 --> 00:04:16.390 align:middle line:10%
I think that
Christopher Nolan is

00:04:16.390 --> 00:04:20.106 align:middle line:10%
burying all sorts of messages
that he wants to be unravelled.

00:04:20.106 --> 00:04:21.480 align:middle line:84%
And Jay and I
actually do unravel

00:04:21.480 --> 00:04:25.560 align:middle line:84%
that film later in our
series, "Hollywood Decoded."

00:04:25.560 --> 00:04:29.010 align:middle line:84%
So I think that it's
both reaching back.

00:04:29.010 --> 00:04:33.180 align:middle line:84%
It's showing people what has
already existed in films.

00:04:33.180 --> 00:04:36.450 align:middle line:84%
And then we're kind of
co-creating a future in films,

00:04:36.450 --> 00:04:40.140 align:middle line:84%
where filmmakers are
adding in things, messages,

00:04:40.140 --> 00:04:42.997 align:middle line:84%
because they know that there's
people out there drilling down,

00:04:42.997 --> 00:04:43.830 align:middle line:90%
which is what we do.

00:04:43.830 --> 00:04:45.990 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Is there some
governmental agency

00:04:45.990 --> 00:04:48.030 align:middle line:84%
that is going to
Hollywood and saying

00:04:48.030 --> 00:04:51.210 align:middle line:84%
look, put in information
about these conspiracies,

00:04:51.210 --> 00:04:54.120 align:middle line:84%
or put in these
things about UFOs.

00:04:54.120 --> 00:04:56.160 align:middle line:90%
Is some organization doing that?

00:04:56.160 --> 00:04:58.310 align:middle line:90%
>>WEIDNER: Yes.

00:04:58.310 --> 00:05:03.610 align:middle line:84%
I think that Hollywood is
being run by some agency.

00:05:03.610 --> 00:05:05.110 align:middle line:90%
I don't know who--

00:05:05.110 --> 00:05:07.920 align:middle line:84%
intel agency, that
is making sure

00:05:07.920 --> 00:05:10.410 align:middle line:84%
there are slow leaks
of information.

00:05:10.410 --> 00:05:12.630 align:middle line:90%
And also information withheld.

00:05:12.630 --> 00:05:15.880 align:middle line:84%
And aliens are a
perfect example.

00:05:15.880 --> 00:05:19.040 align:middle line:10%
If you really follow
Hollywood from the '50s on,

00:05:19.040 --> 00:05:22.140 align:middle line:10%
you can see there's
a slow revealing

00:05:22.140 --> 00:05:24.540 align:middle line:10%
of the alien interaction
with the human race.

00:05:24.540 --> 00:05:27.280 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Kind of getting us
abreast of what's going on.

00:05:27.280 --> 00:05:29.760 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: That's right,
get us used to an idea.

00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:31.860 align:middle line:10%
And also, the same
thing with conspiracy.

00:05:31.860 --> 00:05:35.070 align:middle line:10%
Hollywood is more and more
dealing with conspiracy.

00:05:35.070 --> 00:05:36.900 align:middle line:10%
Because we're beginning
to figure out that

00:05:36.900 --> 00:05:39.000 align:middle line:10%
there actually is conspiracies.

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:41.280 align:middle line:10%
But also, conspiracies
are great entertainment.

00:05:41.280 --> 00:05:44.592 align:middle line:84%
I mean, Shakespeare's greatest
plays are conspiracies.

00:05:44.592 --> 00:05:45.675 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure, absolutely.

00:05:45.675 --> 00:05:46.966 align:middle line:90%
>>WEIDNER: "Hamlet," "Macbeth."

00:05:46.966 --> 00:05:49.420 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: Yeah, I think that
when I was doing my research,

00:05:49.420 --> 00:05:52.260 align:middle line:84%
I came across actually
academic text that

00:05:52.260 --> 00:05:54.660 align:middle line:84%
discussed the relationship
between the intelligence

00:05:54.660 --> 00:05:56.300 align:middle line:90%
agencies and Hollywood.

00:05:56.300 --> 00:05:59.550 align:middle line:84%
And so most of the 16 or so that
we know, intelligence agencies,

00:05:59.550 --> 00:06:02.970 align:middle line:84%
actually have liaison
offices with various studios.

00:06:02.970 --> 00:06:06.782 align:middle line:84%
And so it's just like you said,
they actually can say at times,

00:06:06.782 --> 00:06:09.240 align:middle line:84%
we want this message here, we
don't want this message here.

00:06:09.240 --> 00:06:11.490 align:middle line:84%
You need to alter the
script a little bit here.

00:06:11.490 --> 00:06:15.110 align:middle line:84%
Again, written by university
professors, two or three books

00:06:15.110 --> 00:06:15.990 align:middle line:90%
I came across.

00:06:15.990 --> 00:06:16.830 align:middle line:90%
This blew me away.

00:06:16.830 --> 00:06:18.870 align:middle line:84%
Because I had no
idea that there was

00:06:18.870 --> 00:06:22.400 align:middle line:84%
such an intimate relationship
between the Pentagon

00:06:22.400 --> 00:06:23.200 align:middle line:90%
and Hollywood.

00:06:23.200 --> 00:06:23.730 align:middle line:90%
But it's all there.

00:06:23.730 --> 00:06:24.530 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It's huge.

00:06:24.530 --> 00:06:27.120 align:middle line:10%
Lamar Waldron, who's been on
"Coast to Coast" and "Beyond

00:06:27.120 --> 00:06:30.210 align:middle line:10%
Belief," has written books
about the JFK assassination,

00:06:30.210 --> 00:06:34.500 align:middle line:10%
wrote in his book that the
CIA has a division that

00:06:34.500 --> 00:06:37.380 align:middle line:10%
does nothing but deal with
the media, which includes

00:06:37.380 --> 00:06:41.400 align:middle line:10%
Hollywood, trying to get
them to control what they say

00:06:41.400 --> 00:06:44.100 align:middle line:10%
or to say something that
the government wants

00:06:44.100 --> 00:06:46.170 align:middle line:10%
them to know about and say.

00:06:46.170 --> 00:06:48.954 align:middle line:84%
Who would think about
that, years ago?

00:06:48.954 --> 00:06:51.120 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: Well, William
Colby, the head of the CIA,

00:06:51.120 --> 00:06:54.600 align:middle line:84%
said that he plays the press
like a giant Wurlitzer.

00:06:54.600 --> 00:06:56.630 align:middle line:90%
So that was in the '60s.

00:06:56.630 --> 00:06:58.950 align:middle line:84%
And we know around the
JFK assassination, all

00:06:58.950 --> 00:07:00.780 align:middle line:84%
of the interplay of
intelligence agencies,

00:07:00.780 --> 00:07:03.330 align:middle line:84%
trying to hide what
was really going on.

00:07:03.330 --> 00:07:06.360 align:middle line:10%
And then Oliver Stone
made his great film in '91

00:07:06.360 --> 00:07:10.590 align:middle line:10%
about JFK, in which the
"Washington Post" reviewed

00:07:10.590 --> 00:07:12.840 align:middle line:10%
the film before it came out.

00:07:12.840 --> 00:07:15.810 align:middle line:84%
The first time that a
film was actually reviewed

00:07:15.810 --> 00:07:17.230 align:middle line:90%
at all before it came out.

00:07:17.230 --> 00:07:19.220 align:middle line:84%
And it was a huge
negative review.

00:07:19.220 --> 00:07:21.165 align:middle line:84%
And the "Washington Post"
has ties to the CIA.

00:07:21.165 --> 00:07:21.510 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure.

00:07:21.510 --> 00:07:24.030 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: So we're looking
at this, and saying, yeah,

00:07:24.030 --> 00:07:25.030 align:middle line:90%
this is what's going on.

00:07:25.030 --> 00:07:26.613 align:middle line:84%
We just have to come
to grips with it.

00:07:26.613 --> 00:07:29.670 align:middle line:84%
I don't think that the CIA
actually took over Hollywood

00:07:29.670 --> 00:07:31.591 align:middle line:90%
until the late '70s.

00:07:31.591 --> 00:07:33.090 align:middle line:10%
They think you can
see, if you watch

00:07:33.090 --> 00:07:36.720 align:middle line:10%
films, that there
was a kind of a tenor

00:07:36.720 --> 00:07:39.870 align:middle line:10%
to the films of the '70s, very
rebellious, very revealing,

00:07:39.870 --> 00:07:41.460 align:middle line:10%
very conspiratorial.

00:07:41.460 --> 00:07:44.100 align:middle line:84%
And then "The Godfather,"
actually talking

00:07:44.100 --> 00:07:46.530 align:middle line:84%
about the mafia
for the first time.

00:07:46.530 --> 00:07:49.420 align:middle line:84%
And all this, and
then around '79, '80,

00:07:49.420 --> 00:07:51.780 align:middle line:84%
you see a sudden
shift in the way

00:07:51.780 --> 00:07:53.970 align:middle line:84%
that films are more
blockbustery, less

00:07:53.970 --> 00:07:56.209 align:middle line:84%
controversial,
and I think that's

00:07:56.209 --> 00:07:57.750 align:middle line:84%
when they started
coming in and said,

00:07:57.750 --> 00:07:59.670 align:middle line:84%
uh, you guys, we've
had enough of that.

00:07:59.670 --> 00:08:01.684 align:middle line:84%
We're not going
reveal any more truths

00:08:01.684 --> 00:08:02.850 align:middle line:90%
that you guys are revealing.

00:08:02.850 --> 00:08:03.360 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Don't go there.

00:08:03.360 --> 00:08:04.443 align:middle line:90%
>>WEIDNER: Don't go there.

00:08:04.443 --> 00:08:06.660 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: There's actually
a movie about this topic

00:08:06.660 --> 00:08:07.616 align:middle line:90%
called "Wag the Dog."

00:08:07.616 --> 00:08:08.865 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Oh, yeah, absolutely.

00:08:08.865 --> 00:08:09.820 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: A lot of people
are probably familiar with,

00:08:09.820 --> 00:08:11.080 align:middle line:90%
in the early '90s and--

00:08:11.080 --> 00:08:12.440 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: With Dustin Hoffman.

00:08:12.440 --> 00:08:12.700 align:middle line:90%
>>DYER: Exactly.

00:08:12.700 --> 00:08:14.269 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: He plays
Stanley Kubrick.

00:08:14.269 --> 00:08:16.560 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: And then you have
the Robert De Niro character,

00:08:16.560 --> 00:08:19.230 align:middle line:84%
who is more or less the liaison
who's kind of telling him

00:08:19.230 --> 00:08:21.450 align:middle line:84%
what to do and how the
scripts going to be.

00:08:21.450 --> 00:08:24.090 align:middle line:10%
And they even kind of create
a fake war in Albania,

00:08:24.090 --> 00:08:26.230 align:middle line:10%
with Kirsten Dunst, is
actually a young girl.

00:08:26.230 --> 00:08:27.896 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: With a blue
screen behind them.

00:08:27.896 --> 00:08:30.799 align:middle line:10%
>>DYER: She's holding
Tostitos, and they Photoshop--

00:08:30.799 --> 00:08:31.840 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Etched them out.

00:08:31.840 --> 00:08:32.640 align:middle line:90%
>>DYER: Right.

00:08:32.640 --> 00:08:34.770 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Yeah, and the
Dustin Hoffman character

00:08:34.770 --> 00:08:36.270 align:middle line:90%
is named Stanley.

00:08:36.270 --> 00:08:37.645 align:middle line:84%
And he's clearly
Stanley Kubrick.

00:08:37.645 --> 00:08:39.978 align:middle line:84%
And he's running around saying
this is my greatest work,

00:08:39.978 --> 00:08:42.240 align:middle line:84%
this is my greatest work, I
want the world to know it.

00:08:42.240 --> 00:08:44.790 align:middle line:84%
And then Robert De Niro
says, uh-uh, uh-uh.

00:08:44.790 --> 00:08:47.050 align:middle line:90%
And then Dustin Hoffman dies.

00:08:47.050 --> 00:08:51.660 align:middle line:84%
And so I think that the
director, whose name escapes me

00:08:51.660 --> 00:08:53.280 align:middle line:84%
at the moment, was
trying to show us

00:08:53.280 --> 00:08:55.539 align:middle line:84%
that Stanley Kubrick was
involved in this stuff.

00:08:55.539 --> 00:08:57.330 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Now when we
talk about the meaning

00:08:57.330 --> 00:08:59.470 align:middle line:84%
of esoteric films,
exactly what are

00:08:59.470 --> 00:09:00.720 align:middle line:90%
we talking about first of all?

00:09:00.720 --> 00:09:03.360 align:middle line:84%
For a "Beyond Belief"
audience, what

00:09:03.360 --> 00:09:06.990 align:middle line:84%
does esoteric mean when you're
dealing with these films?

00:09:06.990 --> 00:09:10.120 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: Well, esoteric
means inner, hidden.

00:09:10.120 --> 00:09:11.700 align:middle line:84%
And then esoteric
is the opposite

00:09:11.700 --> 00:09:13.440 align:middle line:84%
of that, which is
public and revealed.

00:09:13.440 --> 00:09:15.930 align:middle line:84%
And so I titled my
book that because I

00:09:15.930 --> 00:09:17.430 align:middle line:84%
felt like there was
so much going on

00:09:17.430 --> 00:09:19.846 align:middle line:84%
in films that it was actually
multi-layered, multi-tiered.

00:09:19.846 --> 00:09:23.460 align:middle line:84%
And you can have the level which
is kind of the surface meaning,

00:09:23.460 --> 00:09:26.170 align:middle line:84%
or like if you talk
about great literature,

00:09:26.170 --> 00:09:29.000 align:middle line:84%
if you have a college class, you
might do a close reading, which

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:30.750 align:middle line:84%
is where you're picking
apart the symbols,

00:09:30.750 --> 00:09:32.825 align:middle line:84%
and the imagery, and
the foreshadowing.

00:09:32.825 --> 00:09:34.950 align:middle line:84%
But then it goes deeper
than that, because you also

00:09:34.950 --> 00:09:37.890 align:middle line:84%
have kind of occult, or esoteric
meanings in a lot of films,

00:09:37.890 --> 00:09:40.050 align:middle line:84%
like "2001" or "Eyes
Wide Shut," where

00:09:40.050 --> 00:09:42.090 align:middle line:84%
we're dealing with
secret societies,

00:09:42.090 --> 00:09:43.900 align:middle line:90%
and metaphysics, and gods.

00:09:43.900 --> 00:09:44.700 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Real life.

00:09:44.700 --> 00:09:46.140 align:middle line:90%
>>DYER: Exactly.

00:09:46.140 --> 00:09:47.850 align:middle line:84%
And then there's
also layers where

00:09:47.850 --> 00:09:50.010 align:middle line:84%
there might be government
propaganda, where

00:09:50.010 --> 00:09:54.150 align:middle line:84%
the establishment is essentially
trying to socially engineer

00:09:54.150 --> 00:09:57.430 align:middle line:84%
and nudge or turn the population
in a certain direction.

00:09:57.430 --> 00:09:59.840 align:middle line:84%
So it can really just go off
in all kinds of directions

00:09:59.840 --> 00:10:02.452 align:middle line:84%
if you know how to
decode those layers.

00:10:02.452 --> 00:10:03.660 align:middle line:90%
And that's what we try to do.

00:10:03.660 --> 00:10:05.035 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: When you
wrote the book,

00:10:05.035 --> 00:10:08.790 align:middle line:84%
"Esoteric Hollywood," what was
the impetus to write the book?

00:10:08.790 --> 00:10:11.400 align:middle line:84%
What did you first
see that made you say,

00:10:11.400 --> 00:10:13.710 align:middle line:90%
well, there's more to this?

00:10:13.710 --> 00:10:15.760 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: I think when
I was in high school,

00:10:15.760 --> 00:10:17.390 align:middle line:84%
I really developed
a love for film.

00:10:17.390 --> 00:10:19.115 align:middle line:10%
And I remember back
in the late '90s,

00:10:19.115 --> 00:10:21.890 align:middle line:10%
"Conspiracy Theory" came
out, the Dick Donner film

00:10:21.890 --> 00:10:23.100 align:middle line:10%
with Mel Gibson.

00:10:23.100 --> 00:10:26.810 align:middle line:84%
And the whole plot is Mel
Gibson is this former MKUltra

00:10:26.810 --> 00:10:27.660 align:middle line:90%
survivor.

00:10:27.660 --> 00:10:28.460 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure.

00:10:28.460 --> 00:10:30.830 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: Who has all this
triggered memory coming back.

00:10:30.830 --> 00:10:32.329 align:middle line:84%
And he doesn't know
what's going on.

00:10:32.329 --> 00:10:34.550 align:middle line:84%
And he's running this
little conspiracy magazine.

00:10:34.550 --> 00:10:37.310 align:middle line:84%
And I remember watching
that and thinking there's

00:10:37.310 --> 00:10:38.670 align:middle line:90%
something going on here.

00:10:38.670 --> 00:10:41.360 align:middle line:84%
Why is this film talking
about MKUltra, what's MKUltra?

00:10:41.360 --> 00:10:43.070 align:middle line:84%
So it just kind of
piqued my interest

00:10:43.070 --> 00:10:45.019 align:middle line:84%
to start looking
into these topics

00:10:45.019 --> 00:10:46.060 align:middle line:90%
back when I was 17 or 18.

00:10:46.060 --> 00:10:48.050 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It was like a
domino effect after that.

00:10:48.050 --> 00:10:48.200 align:middle line:90%
>>DYER: Exactly.

00:10:48.200 --> 00:10:50.300 align:middle line:84%
And then you start noticing that
there's all these other films

00:10:50.300 --> 00:10:51.530 align:middle line:90%
that have similar topics.

00:10:51.530 --> 00:10:54.190 align:middle line:84%
I liked "The Godfather"
trilogy quite a bit,

00:10:54.190 --> 00:10:55.560 align:middle line:90%
that Jay mentioned.

00:10:55.560 --> 00:10:58.130 align:middle line:10%
And you notice, that
especially in "Godfather II,"

00:10:58.130 --> 00:11:01.430 align:middle line:10%
it's all about the mob working
together with the government,

00:11:01.430 --> 00:11:04.220 align:middle line:10%
in terms of how to
corrupt senators

00:11:04.220 --> 00:11:05.480 align:middle line:10%
and how to coerce them.

00:11:05.480 --> 00:11:08.390 align:middle line:84%
And then, in "Part
III," Michael Corleone

00:11:08.390 --> 00:11:13.559 align:middle line:84%
becomes this global, basically
private foundation operator.

00:11:13.559 --> 00:11:15.350 align:middle line:84%
And you start noticing,
oh, that's actually

00:11:15.350 --> 00:11:16.550 align:middle line:90%
how the world really works.

00:11:16.550 --> 00:11:17.690 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Exactly.

00:11:17.690 --> 00:11:20.030 align:middle line:84%
So of all the filmmakers
that have been out there,

00:11:20.030 --> 00:11:22.310 align:middle line:90%
who's the most esoteric one?

00:11:22.310 --> 00:11:24.480 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: We're probably
going to agree and disagree.

00:11:24.480 --> 00:11:27.230 align:middle line:10%
I think that number one,
I have to agree with Jay,

00:11:27.230 --> 00:11:28.995 align:middle line:10%
probably Kubrick.

00:11:28.995 --> 00:11:29.870 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: I would too.

00:11:29.870 --> 00:11:32.450 align:middle line:10%
>>DYER: I'm going to say number
two, actually David Lynch.

00:11:32.450 --> 00:11:34.590 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: And how
about Oliver Stone?

00:11:34.590 --> 00:11:36.319 align:middle line:10%
>>DYER: Yes, in many ways, yeah.

00:11:36.319 --> 00:11:37.860 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But Kubrick,
of course, when

00:11:37.860 --> 00:11:39.360 align:middle line:84%
he came out with
some of his movies,

00:11:39.360 --> 00:11:43.260 align:middle line:84%
and we'll talk about a few more,
"Space Odyssey," "2001: A Space

00:11:43.260 --> 00:11:47.920 align:middle line:84%
Odyssey," when I first watched
that, and I was much younger,

00:11:47.920 --> 00:11:49.188 align:middle line:90%
I didn't get it right away.

00:11:49.188 --> 00:11:49.988 align:middle line:90%
