00:12:39.900 --> 00:12:41.420 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Jay, what
did that scene mean?

00:12:41.420 --> 00:12:42.836 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: Well,
it's interesting.

00:12:42.836 --> 00:12:45.850 align:middle line:84%
There was a famous incident
when they showed "2001: A Space

00:12:45.850 --> 00:12:49.210 align:middle line:84%
Odyssey" in Hollywood, at the
Hollywood Dome, the Cinerama

00:12:49.210 --> 00:12:51.190 align:middle line:84%
Theater there on
Sunset Boulevard.

00:12:51.190 --> 00:12:53.660 align:middle line:84%
Rock Hudson, about
halfway through the film,

00:12:53.660 --> 00:12:56.990 align:middle line:84%
stood up and went I don't
know what this movie is about,

00:12:56.990 --> 00:12:59.290 align:middle line:90%
and stormed out of the theater.

00:12:59.290 --> 00:13:01.120 align:middle line:84%
And I think a lot
of people did that.

00:13:01.120 --> 00:13:04.020 align:middle line:84%
I know my dad, when he saw it,
he stormed out of the theater.

00:13:04.020 --> 00:13:06.680 align:middle line:90%
A lot of people didn't get it.

00:13:06.680 --> 00:13:08.180 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Stormed
out in frustration?

00:13:08.180 --> 00:13:09.490 align:middle line:90%
>>WEIDNER: Yeah, frustration.

00:13:09.490 --> 00:13:10.940 align:middle line:90%
I was exact opposite.

00:13:10.940 --> 00:13:14.020 align:middle line:84%
I was completely entranced and
could not get out of my seat.

00:13:14.020 --> 00:13:16.980 align:middle line:84%
And the usher had to literally
come and tell me to leave,

00:13:16.980 --> 00:13:18.130 align:middle line:90%
that it was time to go.

00:13:18.130 --> 00:13:19.380 align:middle line:90%
And I couldn't get on my seat.

00:13:19.380 --> 00:13:21.940 align:middle line:84%
And I was stunned for like
three days after I saw the film.

00:13:21.940 --> 00:13:23.830 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: So you get this.

00:13:23.830 --> 00:13:25.240 align:middle line:90%
>>WEIDNER: I didn't get it.

00:13:25.240 --> 00:13:28.330 align:middle line:84%
I knew that something was
happening that I should get,

00:13:28.330 --> 00:13:29.440 align:middle line:90%
but I didn't know why.

00:13:29.440 --> 00:13:31.750 align:middle line:84%
It took me years
really to unveil

00:13:31.750 --> 00:13:32.900 align:middle line:90%
what was really going on.

00:13:32.900 --> 00:13:35.620 align:middle line:84%
I must have seen
it 20 or 30 times.

00:13:35.620 --> 00:13:40.390 align:middle line:84%
And I began realizing,
as I matured, and studied

00:13:40.390 --> 00:13:43.270 align:middle line:84%
philosophy, and alchemy,
and esotericism,

00:13:43.270 --> 00:13:46.840 align:middle line:84%
that Kubrick was heavily
enmeshed in these subjects.

00:13:46.840 --> 00:13:50.950 align:middle line:84%
And then after he died,
I talked to a person who

00:13:50.950 --> 00:13:53.210 align:middle line:90%
worked at his estate in London.

00:13:53.210 --> 00:13:55.510 align:middle line:84%
He said, oh, yeah,
he had whole shelves,

00:13:55.510 --> 00:13:58.960 align:middle line:84%
a library full of
alchemy books, philosophy

00:13:58.960 --> 00:14:01.690 align:middle line:90%
books on hermetic traditions.

00:14:01.690 --> 00:14:03.104 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Right,
he was into this.

00:14:03.104 --> 00:14:04.520 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: He was
totally into it.

00:14:04.520 --> 00:14:05.800 align:middle line:90%
It was his life.

00:14:05.800 --> 00:14:09.280 align:middle line:10%
And I think that he had a
plan at the end of his life

00:14:09.280 --> 00:14:14.380 align:middle line:10%
to do "Eyes Wide Shut" and then
"AI" as a kind of final bookend

00:14:14.380 --> 00:14:16.930 align:middle line:10%
to what he was really
trying to express

00:14:16.930 --> 00:14:21.922 align:middle line:10%
about both esotericism, but also
his fears of secret societies

00:14:21.922 --> 00:14:23.380 align:middle line:10%
and where they're
going to take us,

00:14:23.380 --> 00:14:26.320 align:middle line:10%
if they keep going
on unchecked, which

00:14:26.320 --> 00:14:28.210 align:middle line:10%
is what I think
both of those films

00:14:28.210 --> 00:14:29.710 align:middle line:10%
were originally
going to be about.

00:14:29.710 --> 00:14:32.270 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And died before he
finished "Eyes Wide Shut."

00:14:32.270 --> 00:14:33.228 align:middle line:90%
>>WEIDNER: Yes, he did.

00:14:33.228 --> 00:14:35.860 align:middle line:84%
And I believe they
re-edited "Eyes Wide Shut"

00:14:35.860 --> 00:14:39.070 align:middle line:84%
and took huge chunks of
important material out of it.

00:14:39.070 --> 00:14:42.037 align:middle line:84%
I was told by one of his top
assistants that this was so.

00:14:42.037 --> 00:14:43.870 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And that was
another esoteric movie

00:14:43.870 --> 00:14:47.650 align:middle line:84%
I didn't get until you
watch it three, four times.

00:14:47.650 --> 00:14:49.240 align:middle line:84%
And then it starts
to dawn on you,

00:14:49.240 --> 00:14:51.340 align:middle line:84%
hey, this is a little
symbolism, they're

00:14:51.340 --> 00:14:52.750 align:middle line:90%
trying to tell us something.

00:14:52.750 --> 00:14:56.440 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: Yeah, and
Kubrick, when I first

00:14:56.440 --> 00:15:00.700 align:middle line:84%
started arguing that Kubrick was
placing symbols into his films,

00:15:00.700 --> 00:15:02.500 align:middle line:84%
this was before "Eyes
Wide Shut" came out.

00:15:02.500 --> 00:15:03.300 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:15:03.300 --> 00:15:05.800 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: People,
basically I was chastised

00:15:05.800 --> 00:15:07.960 align:middle line:84%
and called kind of--
you're just seeing

00:15:07.960 --> 00:15:09.190 align:middle line:90%
things that aren't there.

00:15:09.190 --> 00:15:12.220 align:middle line:84%
And then "Eyes Wide Shut"
came out exactly 30 years

00:15:12.220 --> 00:15:16.920 align:middle line:84%
after the Apollo launch,
and when people saw that,

00:15:16.920 --> 00:15:17.720 align:middle line:90%
that was it.

00:15:17.720 --> 00:15:19.070 align:middle line:90%
They all said, you're right.

00:15:19.070 --> 00:15:21.130 align:middle line:84%
This guy is obviously
doing things

00:15:21.130 --> 00:15:23.170 align:middle line:84%
that we did not
realize in his films.

00:15:23.170 --> 00:15:26.050 align:middle line:84%
And we all have to go
back and take a closer

00:15:26.050 --> 00:15:27.490 align:middle line:90%
look at all of his films.

00:15:27.490 --> 00:15:30.880 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Was he, in your
opinion, being told what to do?

00:15:30.880 --> 00:15:32.660 align:middle line:90%
Or was he doing this on his own?

00:15:32.660 --> 00:15:34.270 align:middle line:10%
>>WEIDNER: He was
being told what

00:15:34.270 --> 00:15:37.840 align:middle line:10%
to do in "2001:
A Space Odyssey."

00:15:37.840 --> 00:15:40.870 align:middle line:10%
That was definitely the
government telling him

00:15:40.870 --> 00:15:44.374 align:middle line:10%
that we're going to reforge the
future, as far as space travel,

00:15:44.374 --> 00:15:45.290 align:middle line:10%
or what it looks like.

00:15:45.290 --> 00:15:48.160 align:middle line:84%
And he had major
corporations behind him,

00:15:48.160 --> 00:15:52.450 align:middle line:84%
major people in NASA working
with him on "Space Odyssey."

00:15:52.450 --> 00:15:54.100 align:middle line:90%
But I think he cut a deal.

00:15:54.100 --> 00:15:55.750 align:middle line:84%
I'm pretty sure I'm
right about this.

00:15:55.750 --> 00:15:57.220 align:middle line:84%
He's the only
filmmaker, I think,

00:15:57.220 --> 00:15:59.500 align:middle line:84%
because of what he
did for the government

00:15:59.500 --> 00:16:03.280 align:middle line:84%
in "2001: A Space Odyssey," he
got to kind of have a free ride

00:16:03.280 --> 00:16:06.040 align:middle line:84%
and do whatever he wanted
for the rest of his career,

00:16:06.040 --> 00:16:08.000 align:middle line:84%
and "Eyes Wide Shut,"
which was re-edited.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:08.800 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: All right.

00:16:08.800 --> 00:16:11.640 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: But you know, he
did not have anyone re-edit

00:16:11.640 --> 00:16:13.630 align:middle line:90%
"Clockwork Orange."

00:16:13.630 --> 00:16:16.930 align:middle line:10%
He re-edited it after
the controversy arised.

00:16:16.930 --> 00:16:19.750 align:middle line:84%
Same thing with "Barry
Lyndon," all of his films,

00:16:19.750 --> 00:16:21.760 align:middle line:84%
he was in complete
control of them.

00:16:21.760 --> 00:16:26.410 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: The Nazis, Jay
Dyer, understood propaganda.

00:16:26.410 --> 00:16:29.900 align:middle line:84%
They even had a department that
did nothing but propaganda.

00:16:29.900 --> 00:16:31.900 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: Yeah, and this
goes back to the earliest

00:16:31.900 --> 00:16:33.100 align:middle line:90%
days of the camera.

00:16:33.100 --> 00:16:35.970 align:middle line:84%
The camera was known,
even when it was invented,

00:16:35.970 --> 00:16:38.916 align:middle line:84%
that it was going to be a
tremendous tool for propaganda.

00:16:38.916 --> 00:16:41.290 align:middle line:84%
And so the Nazis were some of
the first pioneers of that.

00:16:41.290 --> 00:16:42.580 align:middle line:90%
You're absolutely right.

00:16:42.580 --> 00:16:44.560 align:middle line:84%
And then Hollywood does
the exact same thing.

00:16:44.560 --> 00:16:47.587 align:middle line:84%
Some of the earliest days of
Hollywood were actually Nazis.

00:16:47.587 --> 00:16:49.420 align:middle line:84%
And then you have various
competing factions

00:16:49.420 --> 00:16:52.180 align:middle line:84%
who kind of vied for
control of Hollywood.

00:16:52.180 --> 00:16:55.290 align:middle line:84%
But from the earliest days,
movies were propaganda.

00:16:55.290 --> 00:16:58.570 align:middle line:84%
You can go back to Howard Hughes
in the '20s, "Hell's Angels."

00:16:58.570 --> 00:17:01.361 align:middle line:84%
He was filming giant
war propaganda films.

00:17:01.361 --> 00:17:03.610 align:middle line:10%
Most people don't know that,
but they were propaganda.

00:17:03.610 --> 00:17:05.290 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Maybe even funded
by the government to do that.

00:17:05.290 --> 00:17:06.640 align:middle line:10%
>>DYER: Oh, absolutely.

00:17:06.640 --> 00:17:07.520 align:middle line:10%
>>WEIDNER: I agree.

00:17:07.520 --> 00:17:11.329 align:middle line:10%
And Leni Riefenstahl, who
was Hitler's filmmaker,

00:17:11.329 --> 00:17:15.460 align:middle line:10%
literally hired 30,000 extras
to be at the Nuremberg rally.

00:17:15.460 --> 00:17:17.579 align:middle line:10%
Those weren't people
that were actually Nazis.

00:17:17.579 --> 00:17:18.880 align:middle line:10%
Those were people that she
went out in the streets

00:17:18.880 --> 00:17:20.380 align:middle line:10%
and gathered, on
told them how to act.

00:17:20.380 --> 00:17:22.599 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Made it sound like
they all wanted to follow him.

00:17:22.599 --> 00:17:23.020 align:middle line:10%
>>WEIDNER: Exactly.

00:17:23.020 --> 00:17:24.220 align:middle line:10%
It was all propaganda.

00:17:24.220 --> 00:17:26.140 align:middle line:10%
The entire Nuremberg
rally was nothing

00:17:26.140 --> 00:17:28.060 align:middle line:10%
but staged, the entire thing.

00:17:28.060 --> 00:17:29.860 align:middle line:84%
Same with "The
Olympiad," her great film

00:17:29.860 --> 00:17:32.020 align:middle line:90%
on the 1936 Olympics.

00:17:32.020 --> 00:17:35.140 align:middle line:10%
I mean, that was all staged.

00:17:35.140 --> 00:17:36.880 align:middle line:10%
The cameras were
buried under the pool

00:17:36.880 --> 00:17:38.520 align:middle line:10%
so you could see
all the swimmers,

00:17:38.520 --> 00:17:40.050 align:middle line:10%
and they were all
brilliantly done.

00:17:40.050 --> 00:17:42.460 align:middle line:10%
And in fact, she does
not get enough credit

00:17:42.460 --> 00:17:46.490 align:middle line:10%
by the way for her pioneering
filmmaking propaganda

00:17:46.490 --> 00:17:47.290 align:middle line:10%
abilities.

00:17:47.290 --> 00:17:50.800 align:middle line:84%
And I'm one of her biggest fans
and think, despite the fact

