They knew this thing was coming.

00:26:46.440 --> 00:26:48.030 align:middle line:90%
Let's make this show.

00:26:48.030 --> 00:26:49.270 align:middle line:90%
Let's show that it happened.

00:26:49.270 --> 00:26:50.150 align:middle line:84%
Then when it happens,
it's not going

00:26:50.150 --> 00:26:52.800 align:middle line:84%
to be such a big shock to the
people watching, because they

00:26:52.800 --> 00:26:54.429 align:middle line:90%
saw it already on TV.

00:26:54.429 --> 00:26:56.220 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: I think this
is really an idea that

00:26:56.220 --> 00:27:00.570 align:middle line:84%
comes out of early 20th century
British espionage fiction.

00:27:00.570 --> 00:27:03.070 align:middle line:10%
So you have a lot of writers
like Graham Greene, who

00:27:03.070 --> 00:27:05.460 align:middle line:10%
will write books like,
"Our Man in Havana,"

00:27:05.460 --> 00:27:07.945 align:middle line:10%
and these books will
predict events like--

00:27:07.945 --> 00:27:08.820 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Ian Fleming?

00:27:08.820 --> 00:27:09.760 align:middle line:90%
>>DYER: Exactly.

00:27:09.760 --> 00:27:11.837 align:middle line:84%
They'll predict events
like false flag attacks,

00:27:11.837 --> 00:27:13.920 align:middle line:84%
or whatever, that will
happen a year or two later.

00:27:13.920 --> 00:27:15.450 align:middle line:10%
In fact, you mentioned
Ian Fleming--

00:27:15.450 --> 00:27:18.000 align:middle line:10%
his brother, Peter
Fleming, also wrote a novel

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:23.220 align:middle line:10%
about a flight of a Nazi
leader to Scotland a year

00:27:23.220 --> 00:27:25.674 align:middle line:10%
or two before Rudolf
Hess' famous flight.

00:27:25.674 --> 00:27:27.090 align:middle line:84%
So I think that
what you're seeing

00:27:27.090 --> 00:27:29.500 align:middle line:84%
is this kind of, as he
mentioned, softening up.

00:27:29.500 --> 00:27:33.000 align:middle line:84%
And almost a kind of magic
ritual, voodoo ritual,

00:27:33.000 --> 00:27:35.480 align:middle line:84%
where it's like, oh,
they know what's coming.

00:27:35.480 --> 00:27:38.080 align:middle line:84%
And so you're kind of
deceived into thinking

00:27:38.080 --> 00:27:40.110 align:middle line:84%
that the establishment
has God powers.

00:27:40.110 --> 00:27:42.870 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well, I didn't
know about the passport date

00:27:42.870 --> 00:27:44.010 align:middle line:90%
from "The Matrix."

00:27:44.010 --> 00:27:44.860 align:middle line:90%
That's unbelievable.

00:27:44.860 --> 00:27:45.660 align:middle line:90%
>>WEIDNER: It is.

00:27:45.660 --> 00:27:46.460 align:middle line:90%
And there's others.

00:27:46.460 --> 00:27:48.510 align:middle line:84%
There's a lot of
references actually

00:27:48.510 --> 00:27:52.920 align:middle line:84%
to the 9/11 events going on
in the entertainment industry.

00:27:52.920 --> 00:27:56.260 align:middle line:90%
And it bears further scrutiny.

00:27:56.260 --> 00:27:57.060 align:middle line:90%
Because I'm--

00:27:57.060 --> 00:27:58.690 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It sure does.

00:27:58.690 --> 00:28:00.270 align:middle line:10%
>>WEIDNER: But
again, we also know

00:28:00.270 --> 00:28:04.410 align:middle line:10%
that, as Cliff High has
talked about frequently,

00:28:04.410 --> 00:28:09.920 align:middle line:10%
that people have the ability
to understand future events.

00:28:09.920 --> 00:28:13.260 align:middle line:84%
And he does his
programs, which show

00:28:13.260 --> 00:28:16.890 align:middle line:84%
that people are talking on the
internet about an event that

00:28:16.890 --> 00:28:18.180 align:middle line:90%
hasn't occurred yet.

00:28:18.180 --> 00:28:19.560 align:middle line:90%
And then it will occur.

00:28:19.560 --> 00:28:22.270 align:middle line:84%
And I think that that's
also what's going on here.

00:28:22.270 --> 00:28:24.380 align:middle line:90%
People are naturally psychic.

00:28:24.380 --> 00:28:25.880 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: They are
naturally psychic.

00:28:25.880 --> 00:28:27.290 align:middle line:90%
They have this connection.

00:28:27.290 --> 00:28:29.900 align:middle line:84%
But I don't believe
in coincidences.

00:28:29.900 --> 00:28:34.610 align:middle line:84%
There's just no way somebody
would have injected 9/11

00:28:34.610 --> 00:28:38.450 align:middle line:84%
in a passport in a movie,
or come up with an idea

00:28:38.450 --> 00:28:42.700 align:middle line:84%
that planes are going
to target buildings.

00:28:42.700 --> 00:28:44.800 align:middle line:90%
You don't guess that.

00:28:44.800 --> 00:28:47.200 align:middle line:84%
Somebody's telling
somebody something.

00:28:47.200 --> 00:28:49.900 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: Yeah, and
so close to the event.

00:28:49.900 --> 00:28:51.670 align:middle line:84%
They both happened
before the event,

00:28:51.670 --> 00:28:52.930 align:middle line:90%
but they're pretty close.

00:28:52.930 --> 00:28:56.150 align:middle line:84%
Two years is pretty
close to the event time.

00:28:56.150 --> 00:28:59.440 align:middle line:84%
And so it was definitely
done on purpose.

00:28:59.440 --> 00:29:03.130 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: I think during the
Oklahoma federal building

00:29:03.130 --> 00:29:07.930 align:middle line:10%
bombing that there was
a story or a book that

00:29:07.930 --> 00:29:11.410 align:middle line:10%
had come out prior to
that, wasn't there, Jay?

00:29:11.410 --> 00:29:13.220 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: It's "The Final
Jihad" by Keating,

00:29:13.220 --> 00:29:14.650 align:middle line:90%
who was the governor's brother.

00:29:14.650 --> 00:29:15.250 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's right.

00:29:15.250 --> 00:29:16.749 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: And he
mentions Tim McVeigh.

00:29:16.749 --> 00:29:18.610 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It came out
years before, years

00:29:18.610 --> 00:29:20.710 align:middle line:84%
before the actual
event happened.

00:29:20.710 --> 00:29:23.110 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: Tim McVeigh,
instead of--

00:29:23.110 --> 00:29:27.130 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: Also, five years
before the Titanic sunk,

00:29:27.130 --> 00:29:31.450 align:middle line:84%
there was a novel called "The
Titan," about a super ship

00:29:31.450 --> 00:29:34.244 align:middle line:84%
called The Titan, which
sinks by hitting an iceberg

00:29:34.244 --> 00:29:35.410 align:middle line:90%
and kills everyone on board.

00:29:35.410 --> 00:29:37.150 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Go figure, go figure.

00:29:37.150 --> 00:29:39.441 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: I think there's two
things that work with that.

00:29:39.441 --> 00:29:42.250 align:middle line:84%
And I think sometimes it's
intelligence agencies telling,

00:29:42.250 --> 00:29:43.186 align:middle line:90%
feeding information.

00:29:43.186 --> 00:29:44.560 align:middle line:84%
I also think that
at times people

00:29:44.560 --> 00:29:47.800 align:middle line:84%
have a kind of artistic
inspiration or sense

00:29:47.800 --> 00:29:48.740 align:middle line:90%
of what's coming.

00:29:48.740 --> 00:29:51.130 align:middle line:10%
So an example of that
would be, there's

00:29:51.130 --> 00:29:54.040 align:middle line:10%
a famous Dostoyevsky novel
from the late 1800s, called

00:29:54.040 --> 00:29:54.970 align:middle line:10%
"Demons."

00:29:54.970 --> 00:29:58.150 align:middle line:84%
And in that novel, he predicts
a socialist revolution

00:29:58.150 --> 00:30:03.040 align:middle line:84%
that will come on top of
millions of skulls for Russia.

00:30:03.040 --> 00:30:05.890 align:middle line:90%
That's 20, 30 years before 1917.

00:30:05.890 --> 00:30:07.030 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Which happened.

00:30:07.030 --> 00:30:10.300 align:middle line:84%
When you talked about
"The Matrix" again,

00:30:10.300 --> 00:30:14.380 align:middle line:84%
there's a genius behind
these movies, isn't there?

00:30:14.380 --> 00:30:16.424 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: It's
questionable, you know,

00:30:16.424 --> 00:30:18.340 align:middle line:84%
who's really writing
these at a certain point.

00:30:18.340 --> 00:30:20.620 align:middle line:84%
Yes, the Wachowskis
did write it,

00:30:20.620 --> 00:30:23.500 align:middle line:84%
but you have to
really wonder who's

00:30:23.500 --> 00:30:25.720 align:middle line:84%
lurking really in
the shadows, making

00:30:25.720 --> 00:30:27.250 align:middle line:90%
sure these things are done.

00:30:27.250 --> 00:30:29.590 align:middle line:84%
And I think that there is,
as Jay has pointed out,

00:30:29.590 --> 00:30:32.020 align:middle line:84%
an intel agency that's
at the heart of this.

00:30:32.020 --> 00:30:34.630 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: We have a little
clip of that "Matrix" passport

00:30:34.630 --> 00:30:35.430 align:middle line:90%
scene.

00:30:35.430 --> 00:30:36.710 align:middle line:90%
Let's-- this fascinates me.

00:30:36.710 --> 00:30:38.036 align:middle line:90%
Let's have a look at it.

00:30:38.036 --> 00:30:38.836 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:30:38.836 --> 00:30:42.190 align:middle line:10%
>> You have a Social Security
number, you pay your taxes,

00:30:42.190 --> 00:30:47.650 align:middle line:10%
and you help your landlady
carry out her garbage.

00:30:47.650 --> 00:30:51.250 align:middle line:90%


00:30:51.250 --> 00:30:54.560 align:middle line:10%
The other life is
lived in computers,

00:30:54.560 --> 00:30:57.970 align:middle line:10%
where you go by the
hacker alias Neo

00:30:57.970 --> 00:31:00.790 align:middle line:10%
and are guilty of
virtually every computer

00:31:00.790 --> 00:31:01.970 align:middle line:10%
crime we have a law for.

00:31:01.970 --> 00:31:02.770 align:middle line:90%
[END PLAYBACK]

00:31:02.770 --> 00:31:03.894 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah it's uncanny.

00:31:03.894 --> 00:31:05.570 align:middle line:84%
You could actually
see the date there.

00:31:05.570 --> 00:31:09.140 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: Yeah, again
though, unless you had a DV--

00:31:09.140 --> 00:31:10.660 align:middle line:90%
we didn't even have DVDs then--

00:31:10.660 --> 00:31:11.824 align:middle line:90%
if you had a videotape--

00:31:11.824 --> 00:31:13.490 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: --you wouldn't
have caught that.

00:31:13.490 --> 00:31:15.115 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: You wouldn't
have caught it.

00:31:15.115 --> 00:31:19.600 align:middle line:84%
And so, again, when videotape
became ever present,

00:31:19.600 --> 00:31:21.500 align:middle line:84%
then they could
freeze frame stuff.

00:31:21.500 --> 00:31:23.470 align:middle line:84%
And so it came
easier for filmmakers

00:31:23.470 --> 00:31:25.189 align:middle line:84%
to add more things
in because people

00:31:25.189 --> 00:31:26.480 align:middle line:90%
are at home freeze framing it--

00:31:26.480 --> 00:31:26.980 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure.

00:31:26.980 --> 00:31:28.480 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: --and
looking for things.

00:31:28.480 --> 00:31:30.850 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: A lot of people would
be skeptical of the idea

00:31:30.850 --> 00:31:33.580 align:middle line:84%
that you could have
something that detailed

00:31:33.580 --> 00:31:35.040 align:middle line:90%
on purpose and intentional.

00:31:35.040 --> 00:31:37.360 align:middle line:84%
But if you watch a lot of
director's commentaries,

00:31:37.360 --> 00:31:39.880 align:middle line:84%
or even Roger Ebert's
DVD commentaries,

00:31:39.880 --> 00:31:44.770 align:middle line:84%
they will discuss intricacies
and details ad nauseum.

00:31:44.770 --> 00:31:46.240 align:middle line:90%
I mean, it is that intricate.

00:31:46.240 --> 00:31:49.000 align:middle line:84%
Especially directors like
Christopher Nolan or Kubrick,

00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:50.702 align:middle line:84%
they're very attentive
to the details.

00:31:50.702 --> 00:31:52.660 align:middle line:84%
And so these kinds of
things aren't accidental.

00:31:52.660 --> 00:31:54.280 align:middle line:90%
They're not coincidence.

00:31:54.280 --> 00:31:55.880 align:middle line:90%
They're usually on purpose.

00:31:55.880 --> 00:31:59.070 align:middle line:84%
And I think something that's
so significant, like that date,

00:31:59.070 --> 00:32:01.760 align:middle line:84%
and this is 1998, you know
three years ahead of time.

00:32:01.760 --> 00:32:03.404 align:middle line:84%
I don't think that's
a coincidence.

00:32:03.404 --> 00:32:05.320 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: I mean when
Oliver Stone put together

00:32:05.320 --> 00:32:11.020 align:middle line:10%
his "JFK" film, of course,
which truly dug into the Warren

00:32:11.020 --> 00:32:14.890 align:middle line:10%
Commission, and tore
it apart, and really

00:32:14.890 --> 00:32:17.890 align:middle line:10%
backed up the things that
Jim Garrison, the New Orleans

00:32:17.890 --> 00:32:20.890 align:middle line:10%
prosecutor, was
trying to unravel.

00:32:20.890 --> 00:32:22.990 align:middle line:84%
How does he know that
stuff as a director?

00:32:22.990 --> 00:32:25.540 align:middle line:84%
I mean, how does a director
pick up stuff like that?

00:32:25.540 --> 00:32:29.470 align:middle line:84%
Somebody's coming to
him on the outside.

00:32:29.470 --> 00:32:31.630 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: I think
in that case, he

00:32:31.630 --> 00:32:34.300 align:middle line:84%
became fascinated
by the whole thing,

00:32:34.300 --> 00:32:37.090 align:middle line:84%
after watching "The Men
who Killed Kennedy," which

00:32:37.090 --> 00:32:38.590 align:middle line:84%
was a great
documentary series that

00:32:38.590 --> 00:32:42.040 align:middle line:84%
came out about four years
earlier, five years earlier.

00:32:42.040 --> 00:32:46.150 align:middle line:84%
And he apparently became
obsessed, from what I hear.

00:32:46.150 --> 00:32:47.800 align:middle line:90%
And he was into every detail.

00:32:47.800 --> 00:32:50.270 align:middle line:10%
Jim Marrs, he based the
book, off of "Crossfire."

00:32:50.270 --> 00:32:51.460 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: God rest his soul.

00:32:51.460 --> 00:32:52.900 align:middle line:90%
>>WEIDNER: May he rest in peace.

00:32:52.900 --> 00:32:56.080 align:middle line:84%
And I've talked to Jim
quite a bit about it,

00:32:56.080 --> 00:32:59.110 align:middle line:84%
and Jim said that Oliver
would be on the phone all day

00:32:59.110 --> 00:33:04.120 align:middle line:84%
with him, discussing little
tiny details, like was JFK

00:33:04.120 --> 00:33:06.120 align:middle line:90%
wearing a toupee, did he have--

00:33:06.120 --> 00:33:09.830 align:middle line:84%
where was his tie,
why was Jackie's--

00:33:09.830 --> 00:33:12.810 align:middle line:84%
did Jackie get hit by
any blood, and all this.

00:33:12.810 --> 00:33:15.260 align:middle line:90%
And super details.

00:33:15.260 --> 00:33:16.760 align:middle line:90%
And you can see it in the film.

00:33:16.760 --> 00:33:17.890 align:middle line:90%
It's a great film.

00:33:17.890 --> 00:33:19.450 align:middle line:84%
It is the best film that
Oliver Stone ever made.

00:33:19.450 --> 00:33:20.260 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: I think so too.

00:33:20.260 --> 00:33:22.300 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: I think it's one
of the best films ever made.

00:33:22.300 --> 00:33:24.760 align:middle line:84%
I think the acting, the
lighting, the cinematography,

00:33:24.760 --> 00:33:26.962 align:middle line:84%
everything was just
top rate in that film.

00:33:26.962 --> 00:33:28.420 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: You mentioned
Jim Garrison.

00:33:28.420 --> 00:33:30.211 align:middle line:84%
He's actually been in
a few movies as well.

00:33:30.211 --> 00:33:32.128 align:middle line:84%
He shows up in the '80s
movie, "The Big Easy."

00:33:32.128 --> 00:33:32.927 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:33:32.927 --> 00:33:34.270 align:middle line:90%
>>DYER: Which is an interesting.

00:33:34.270 --> 00:33:36.090 align:middle line:90%
There's another tie-in between--

00:33:36.090 --> 00:33:37.900 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And see,
and there was a time

00:33:37.900 --> 00:33:39.730 align:middle line:84%
where the government
tried to portray

00:33:39.730 --> 00:33:41.500 align:middle line:90%
Jim Garrison as a lunatic.

00:33:41.500 --> 00:33:42.850 align:middle line:90%
>>DYER: Right.

00:33:42.850 --> 00:33:44.310 align:middle line:90%
>>WEIDNER: Even Johnny Carson.

00:33:44.310 --> 00:33:45.110 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:33:45.110 --> 00:33:46.360 align:middle line:90%
They put him down.

00:33:46.360 --> 00:33:48.750 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: Somebody had to
tell Johnny Carson this too,

00:33:48.750 --> 00:33:50.740 align:middle line:84%
you've got to make
him look like a fool.

00:33:50.740 --> 00:33:54.790 align:middle line:84%
So does it go all the
way to talk show hosts?

00:33:54.790 --> 00:33:56.362 align:middle line:90%
And the answer is, probably.

00:33:56.362 --> 00:33:57.820 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I've got
to tell you, Jay,

00:33:57.820 --> 00:34:01.900 align:middle line:84%
that I have never been
approached by the government

00:34:01.900 --> 00:34:04.240 align:middle line:90%
to do this or to do that.

00:34:04.240 --> 00:34:07.390 align:middle line:84%
They just have stayed away
from me for some reason.

00:34:07.390 --> 00:34:10.900 align:middle line:84%
With our vast audience, I've
always wondered about that.

00:34:10.900 --> 00:34:14.299 align:middle line:84%
Maybe they're afraid that I'll
say they tried to approach me.

00:34:14.299 --> 00:34:16.590 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: Well, I have to
say, I've never been either.

00:34:16.590 --> 00:34:19.030 align:middle line:84%
I've never had any government
agency ever try to influence

00:34:19.030 --> 00:34:21.159 align:middle line:84%
what I'm doing on
"Gaia" or anything.

00:34:21.159 --> 00:34:23.159 align:middle line:84%
So I think there's
certain people

00:34:23.159 --> 00:34:24.409 align:middle line:90%
that they just stay away from.

00:34:24.409 --> 00:34:25.150 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: They stay away from.

00:34:25.150 --> 00:34:27.691 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: They've already done
an analysis of the personnel,

00:34:27.691 --> 00:34:29.464 align:middle line:84%
and know they'll blow
the beans in public.

00:34:29.464 --> 00:34:30.380 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's right.

00:34:30.380 --> 00:34:31.590 align:middle line:84%
That guy's not
going to play ball.

00:34:31.590 --> 00:34:32.620 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: They're not
going to play ball,

00:34:32.620 --> 00:34:33.850 align:middle line:90%
so there's no point in--

00:34:33.850 --> 00:34:37.159 align:middle line:84%
let him just be suspicious,
but never ever confirm.

00:34:37.159 --> 00:34:39.040 align:middle line:84%
Because don't forget,
if they do come to you

00:34:39.040 --> 00:34:42.850 align:middle line:84%
and tell you what to do, it
confirms your worst suspicions.

00:34:42.850 --> 00:34:46.000 align:middle line:84%
Therefore, you're going to be
going to guns, because you now

00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:48.020 align:middle line:84%
know that this is
exactly what's going on.

00:34:48.020 --> 00:34:51.309 align:middle line:84%
Where now you're not 100% sure
if they're telling people what

00:34:51.309 --> 00:34:53.350 align:middle line:84%
to do, because they've
never told you what to do,

00:34:53.350 --> 00:34:54.370 align:middle line:90%
and I'm in the same boat.

00:34:54.370 --> 00:34:56.020 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Yeah if they're
that concerned about it,

00:34:56.020 --> 00:34:57.394 align:middle line:84%
and they come to
me, then there's

00:34:57.394 --> 00:34:59.511 align:middle line:84%
got to be some fire
behind that smoke.

00:34:59.511 --> 00:35:01.510 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: Absolutely,
and they don't want that.

00:35:01.510 --> 00:35:02.890 align:middle line:84%
That's the last thing
they want is a guy who's

00:35:02.890 --> 00:35:05.050 align:middle line:84%
got millions of people
listening to him on radio

00:35:05.050 --> 00:35:07.050 align:middle line:84%
suddenly start talking
about this gentleman that

00:35:07.050 --> 00:35:09.000 align:middle line:84%
approached him yesterday
at the coffee shop.

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:09.800 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:35:09.800 --> 00:35:12.130 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: Well, conspiracy
theory is the pejorative that

00:35:12.130 --> 00:35:14.050 align:middle line:90%
comes out of the JFK period.

00:35:14.050 --> 00:35:17.260 align:middle line:84%
The CIA actually created that
term as a weaponized term

00:35:17.260 --> 00:35:20.350 align:middle line:84%
for anybody that questioned
the report, oh, that's

00:35:20.350 --> 00:35:21.430 align:middle line:90%
a conspiracy theorist.

00:35:21.430 --> 00:35:22.471 align:middle line:90%
And that actually worked.

00:35:22.471 --> 00:35:24.550 align:middle line:84%
But I think nowadays,
it's kind of backfired.

00:35:24.550 --> 00:35:26.380 align:middle line:84%
And to be a conspiracy
theorist is actually

00:35:26.380 --> 00:35:27.530 align:middle line:90%
to be a reality theorist.

00:35:27.530 --> 00:35:29.499 align:middle line:84%
It's not really a
pejorative anymore.

00:35:29.499 --> 00:35:31.915 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Do you think that
governments, with your program,

00:35:31.915 --> 00:35:34.900 align:middle line:84%
"Hollywood Decoded,"
will continue

00:35:34.900 --> 00:35:38.830 align:middle line:84%
to try to leak information into
films, and television shows,

00:35:38.830 --> 00:35:41.630 align:middle line:84%
and even fake news
with social networking?

00:35:41.630 --> 00:35:43.570 align:middle line:84%
I think we have to add
that to the mix now.

00:35:43.570 --> 00:35:45.361 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: We do, that's
a very good point.

00:35:45.361 --> 00:35:47.680 align:middle line:84%
Because once you realize
that the movies are

00:35:47.680 --> 00:35:51.430 align:middle line:84%
being turned into propaganda
and being weaponized,

00:35:51.430 --> 00:35:53.760 align:middle line:84%
then you have to say to
yourself, OK, is it novels?

00:35:53.760 --> 00:35:54.560 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:35:54.560 --> 00:35:55.400 align:middle line:90%
OK, is it TV shows?

00:35:55.400 --> 00:35:56.320 align:middle line:90%
Oh, yeah.

00:35:56.320 --> 00:35:57.310 align:middle line:90%
Is it new shows?

00:35:57.310 --> 00:35:58.180 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:35:58.180 --> 00:36:01.570 align:middle line:84%
Then you start getting into
the fake news and examining it,

00:36:01.570 --> 00:36:04.300 align:middle line:84%
and you realize that almost
everything you're seeing

00:36:04.300 --> 00:36:05.980 align:middle line:90%
is a contrived incident.

00:36:05.980 --> 00:36:07.844 align:middle line:84%
And they're learning
that from movies.

00:36:07.844 --> 00:36:09.760 align:middle line:84%
They're taking Hollywood
production techniques

00:36:09.760 --> 00:36:13.300 align:middle line:84%
and applying them to news
now, to where they're

00:36:13.300 --> 00:36:17.980 align:middle line:84%
literally having fake actors,
and everything's fake,

00:36:17.980 --> 00:36:21.520 align:middle line:84%
and the lighting is great,
and the acting is great,

00:36:21.520 --> 00:36:24.960 align:middle line:84%
and the production
values are first class.

00:36:24.960 --> 00:36:26.482 align:middle line:10%
And that's troubling.

00:36:26.482 --> 00:36:27.940 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: You mentioned
"The Matrix,"

00:36:27.940 --> 00:36:32.860 align:middle line:84%
there's a scene that we watched
when Neo first pulls a book off

00:36:32.860 --> 00:36:35.770 align:middle line:84%
of his shelf and it's a famous
philosophy book, actually.

00:36:35.770 --> 00:36:40.360 align:middle line:10%
It's called-- it's "Simulacra
and Simulation," by Jean

00:36:40.360 --> 00:36:42.580 align:middle line:10%
Baudrillard, who was a famous
French philosopher, who

00:36:42.580 --> 00:36:45.910 align:middle line:10%
wrote that where we're
going with this tech

00:36:45.910 --> 00:36:49.390 align:middle line:10%
synthetic society is a world
in which the synthetic will

00:36:49.390 --> 00:36:50.970 align:middle line:10%
overlay the real.

00:36:50.970 --> 00:36:54.260 align:middle line:84%
And so I think it's amazing
to me that they stuck that in.

00:36:54.260 --> 00:36:57.604 align:middle line:84%
He's pulling out this book that
deals with that topic, Neo is.

00:36:57.604 --> 00:36:59.770 align:middle line:84%
And that's what we're dealing
with, with mass media,

00:36:59.770 --> 00:37:01.460 align:middle line:90%
is this synthetic overlay--

00:37:01.460 --> 00:37:03.460 align:middle line:84%
it's not the real world
that's really out there,

00:37:03.460 --> 00:37:07.300 align:middle line:84%
but it's the one that the media
kind of gives us as the glasses

00:37:07.300 --> 00:37:09.060 align:middle line:84%
that we're supposed
to interpret reality.

00:37:09.060 --> 00:37:11.500 align:middle line:84%
And it's that's fake
media perception.

00:37:11.500 --> 00:37:12.300 align:middle line:90%
>>WEIDNER: Yeah.

00:37:12.300 --> 00:37:14.320 align:middle line:84%
Wasn't it Bill Casey,
the CIA director,

00:37:14.320 --> 00:37:17.650 align:middle line:84%
he said that when
everybody out there--

00:37:17.650 --> 00:37:20.590 align:middle line:84%
when absolutely everything
they believe is BS,

00:37:20.590 --> 00:37:21.964 align:middle line:90%
we know we've succeeded.

00:37:21.964 --> 00:37:23.380 align:middle line:84%
And that's where
we are right now.

00:37:23.380 --> 00:37:26.269 align:middle line:84%
Everything, nobody has any
footing in reality anymore.

00:37:26.269 --> 00:37:27.310 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: They don't know.

00:37:27.310 --> 00:37:28.487 align:middle line:90%
>>DYER: They are confused.

00:37:28.487 --> 00:37:29.320 align:middle line:90%
>>WEIDNER: They are.

00:37:29.320 --> 00:37:31.690 align:middle line:84%
Hollywood is largely
responsible for that.

00:37:31.690 --> 00:37:32.740 align:middle line:90%
I hate to say it.

00:37:32.740 --> 00:37:34.610 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: James Cameron,
great director.

00:37:34.610 --> 00:37:36.280 align:middle line:10%
Is he told stuff too?

00:37:36.280 --> 00:37:37.530 align:middle line:10%
>>WEIDNER: Yes.

00:37:37.530 --> 00:37:40.680 align:middle line:10%
There's no way that a
former truck driver could

00:37:40.680 --> 00:37:44.070 align:middle line:10%
know what he knows and put
it into "The Terminator,"

00:37:44.070 --> 00:37:48.780 align:middle line:10%
not at that time,
not in 1983, '84.

00:37:48.780 --> 00:37:52.290 align:middle line:84%
DARPA was working on
all of those things,

00:37:52.290 --> 00:37:55.380 align:middle line:84%
but it was super top
secret at the time.

00:37:55.380 --> 00:37:59.625 align:middle line:84%
I heard about it from insiders,
from NASA insiders that they

00:37:59.625 --> 00:38:01.140 align:middle line:84%
were working on
these robots that

00:38:01.140 --> 00:38:03.270 align:middle line:84%
were going to be able
to think independently,

00:38:03.270 --> 00:38:05.500 align:middle line:84%
and they would be used
for law enforcement.

00:38:05.500 --> 00:38:08.800 align:middle line:84%
But that was long before
anybody knew about it.

00:38:08.800 --> 00:38:11.760 align:middle line:84%
And somehow, Cameron knew
about it, and got it right.

00:38:11.760 --> 00:38:12.770 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's amazing.

00:38:12.770 --> 00:38:16.530 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: Even the internet plays
a big role in "The Terminator."

00:38:16.530 --> 00:38:18.660 align:middle line:84%
Nobody in the '80s knew
about the internet,

00:38:18.660 --> 00:38:21.229 align:middle line:84%
unless they worked
in some agency.

00:38:21.229 --> 00:38:23.020 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Right, and
who would predict that?

00:38:23.020 --> 00:38:26.340 align:middle line:84%
Because if you knew,
heck, I'd be buying stock

00:38:26.340 --> 00:38:28.110 align:middle line:90%
at all these emerging companies.

00:38:28.110 --> 00:38:29.910 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: Well, what's
funny is that there

00:38:29.910 --> 00:38:33.060 align:middle line:84%
are all of these '80s
movies and TV shows that

00:38:33.060 --> 00:38:35.790 align:middle line:84%
have the internet, and even
older science fiction stories,

00:38:35.790 --> 00:38:37.320 align:middle line:90%
from Isaac Asimov.

00:38:37.320 --> 00:38:39.047 align:middle line:84%
But if you think about
"The Running Man,"

00:38:39.047 --> 00:38:41.130 align:middle line:84%
there's a famous scene
where in "The Running Man,"

00:38:41.130 --> 00:38:44.250 align:middle line:84%
Arnold Schwarzenegger comes in,
and he orders a plane ticket

00:38:44.250 --> 00:38:46.830 align:middle line:90%
on the info net in the film.

00:38:46.830 --> 00:38:48.060 align:middle line:90%
This is the mid-80's.

00:38:48.060 --> 00:38:49.170 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah, way before.

00:38:49.170 --> 00:38:51.320 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: Yeah, they
we're getting us ready.

00:38:51.320 --> 00:38:54.300 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Who would have
thought that "Avatar" had

00:38:54.300 --> 00:38:55.830 align:middle line:90%
some little messages in there?

00:38:55.830 --> 00:38:56.630 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:38:56.630 --> 00:38:58.960 align:middle line:10%
>> You throw a stick
in the air around here,

00:38:58.960 --> 00:39:03.900 align:middle line:10%
it's going to land on some
