00:39:38.430 --> 00:39:39.870 align:middle line:10%
It's a network.

00:39:39.870 --> 00:39:41.300 align:middle line:10%
It's a global network.

00:39:41.300 --> 00:39:42.960 align:middle line:10%
And the Na'vi can access it.

00:39:42.960 --> 00:39:47.340 align:middle line:10%
They can upload and download
data, memories, at sites

00:39:47.340 --> 00:39:49.377 align:middle line:10%
like the one you just destroyed.

00:39:49.377 --> 00:39:50.808 align:middle line:10%
Yes.

00:39:50.808 --> 00:39:52.085 align:middle line:90%
[END PLAYBACK]

00:39:52.085 --> 00:39:52.960 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Great movie.

00:39:52.960 --> 00:39:53.620 align:middle line:90%
>>WEIDNER: Yeah, great movie.

00:39:53.620 --> 00:39:55.750 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: A lot of
symbolism behind it.

00:39:55.750 --> 00:39:59.470 align:middle line:84%
Did Cameron have some kind
of glimpse into the future?

00:39:59.470 --> 00:40:02.170 align:middle line:10%
>>WEIDNER: Well, yeah,
I think, what my thesis

00:40:02.170 --> 00:40:05.920 align:middle line:10%
is that he had made "Titanic,"
which was the greatest

00:40:05.920 --> 00:40:07.780 align:middle line:10%
grossing film of all time.

00:40:07.780 --> 00:40:10.940 align:middle line:10%
And the hidden message
behind "Titanic" I think

00:40:10.940 --> 00:40:14.410 align:middle line:10%
is that we're witnessing
the end of our world.

00:40:14.410 --> 00:40:18.220 align:middle line:84%
And then he kind
of realized that he

00:40:18.220 --> 00:40:21.920 align:middle line:84%
made kind of a bummer movie
with the end of the world--

00:40:21.920 --> 00:40:22.720 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: A downer.

00:40:22.720 --> 00:40:24.260 align:middle line:90%
>>WEIDNER: A downer.

00:40:24.260 --> 00:40:26.680 align:middle line:84%
So he decided to come
back with his answer

00:40:26.680 --> 00:40:29.830 align:middle line:84%
to what the end of
that world would be,

00:40:29.830 --> 00:40:31.679 align:middle line:84%
and what we could do
to make a newer world.

00:40:31.679 --> 00:40:33.220 align:middle line:10%
And I think that's
what he was trying

00:40:33.220 --> 00:40:35.320 align:middle line:10%
to show in "Avatar,"
that going back

00:40:35.320 --> 00:40:40.197 align:middle line:10%
to a more natural existence,
more of a tribal existence,

00:40:40.197 --> 00:40:42.280 align:middle line:10%
is probably going to be a
better way for us to go.

00:40:42.280 --> 00:40:44.140 align:middle line:84%
And I think that
in the future, we

00:40:44.140 --> 00:40:47.620 align:middle line:84%
are going to go back into a more
rural, bringing our machines

00:40:47.620 --> 00:40:48.580 align:middle line:90%
and our toys with us.

00:40:48.580 --> 00:40:50.680 align:middle line:84%
I think that's
what the answer is.

00:40:50.680 --> 00:40:53.482 align:middle line:84%
That we're probably going
to de-urbanize the world.

00:40:53.482 --> 00:40:55.690 align:middle line:84%
And there's really no point
for people to be piled up

00:40:55.690 --> 00:40:57.114 align:middle line:90%
on top of each other anymore.

00:40:57.114 --> 00:40:59.030 align:middle line:84%
And I think that's
probably where we're going.

00:40:59.030 --> 00:41:00.446 align:middle line:84%
So I think Cameron,
in the end, is

00:41:00.446 --> 00:41:01.960 align:middle line:84%
going to be right
I like that last--

00:41:01.960 --> 00:41:03.400 align:middle line:90%
that scene in particular.

00:41:03.400 --> 00:41:08.380 align:middle line:84%
Because as a person who tries
to talk about spiritual matters,

00:41:08.380 --> 00:41:11.740 align:middle line:84%
and to watch Giovanni
Ribisi's eyes rolling.

00:41:11.740 --> 00:41:13.070 align:middle line:90%
I get that a lot.

00:41:13.070 --> 00:41:15.370 align:middle line:84%
So I really like that scene,
because I'm constantly up

00:41:15.370 --> 00:41:18.760 align:middle line:84%
against people like him,
who cannot comprehend what

00:41:18.760 --> 00:41:20.020 align:middle line:90%
I'm saying.

00:41:20.020 --> 00:41:22.020 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I've seen you
roll your eyes sometimes.

00:41:22.020 --> 00:41:24.130 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: I do roll my
eyes at people like him.

00:41:24.130 --> 00:41:27.760 align:middle line:84%
So that's one of my favorite
scenes in the movie.

00:41:27.760 --> 00:41:31.510 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: As you look at these
films that are emerging today,

00:41:31.510 --> 00:41:34.690 align:middle line:84%
are you seeing something
that we should know about,

00:41:34.690 --> 00:41:38.980 align:middle line:84%
that could occur two, three,
four, or five years from now?

00:41:38.980 --> 00:41:43.480 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: Yes, so many examples
from the past show this.

00:41:43.480 --> 00:41:46.060 align:middle line:84%
So if you look at
Spielberg films, like "AI,"

00:41:46.060 --> 00:41:47.560 align:middle line:84%
you know, we're
seeing, for example,

00:41:47.560 --> 00:41:50.410 align:middle line:84%
sex bots, that are replacing
real relationships.

00:41:50.410 --> 00:41:53.910 align:middle line:84%
That was a big theme in that
movie back in 2000, 2001.

00:41:53.910 --> 00:41:56.260 align:middle line:84%
15 years, 20 years
later, we're seeing it.

00:41:56.260 --> 00:41:58.930 align:middle line:84%
So I think that nowadays what
we can look at in the films

00:41:58.930 --> 00:42:02.080 align:middle line:84%
is what we can expect
15, 20 years from now.

00:42:02.080 --> 00:42:05.770 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Do you see another
9/11 in the movies, for example?

00:42:05.770 --> 00:42:07.020 align:middle line:90%
Do you see anything like that?

00:42:07.020 --> 00:42:08.561 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: Well, I
think that they're

00:42:08.561 --> 00:42:10.600 align:middle line:84%
getting worried about
pulling off events,

00:42:10.600 --> 00:42:14.860 align:middle line:84%
because we're getting so
hip to what they're doing,

00:42:14.860 --> 00:42:18.220 align:middle line:84%
that when they pull
a fake event now,

00:42:18.220 --> 00:42:22.120 align:middle line:84%
they have 50,000 independent
investigators on the internet

00:42:22.120 --> 00:42:23.360 align:middle line:90%
tearing apart the event.

00:42:23.360 --> 00:42:23.570 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:42:23.570 --> 00:42:24.670 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: And they're
getting a little bit worried

00:42:24.670 --> 00:42:27.510 align:middle line:84%
about that, that we're getting
too hip to what they're doing.

00:42:27.510 --> 00:42:30.010 align:middle line:84%
So I've noticed the
events are slowing down.

00:42:30.010 --> 00:42:32.630 align:middle line:84%
They're not pulling those
many fake events anymore.

00:42:32.630 --> 00:42:33.620 align:middle line:90%
I don't know why.

00:42:33.620 --> 00:42:35.090 align:middle line:90%
Maybe it's because of that.

00:42:35.090 --> 00:42:36.700 align:middle line:84%
But what's interesting
is because, I

00:42:36.700 --> 00:42:38.741 align:middle line:84%
think, because of what
Jay and I have been doing,

00:42:38.741 --> 00:42:41.180 align:middle line:84%
not as a direct result,
but as a side result,

00:42:41.180 --> 00:42:43.870 align:middle line:84%
is people are
going to movies now

00:42:43.870 --> 00:42:45.460 align:middle line:84%
that are coming out
now, and looking

00:42:45.460 --> 00:42:48.190 align:middle line:84%
for predictive programming,
in the movies, which has never

00:42:48.190 --> 00:42:49.430 align:middle line:90%
happened before.

00:42:49.430 --> 00:42:50.860 align:middle line:90%
So that's really interesting.

00:42:50.860 --> 00:42:56.050 align:middle line:84%
And what it looks like to me
is that they are planning on

00:42:56.050 --> 00:42:58.810 align:middle line:84%
like creating some kind of
dystopian future of some kind,

00:42:58.810 --> 00:43:02.230 align:middle line:84%
because that's what the themes
of all the modern films,

00:43:02.230 --> 00:43:06.370 align:middle line:84%
over and over again, is
this dystopian, confused,

00:43:06.370 --> 00:43:09.870 align:middle line:84%
chaotic future, which
does not make me feel real

00:43:09.870 --> 00:43:12.370 align:middle line:84%
>>DYER: Well, if we think about
the Lakowski's-- it makes me

00:43:12.370 --> 00:43:15.070 align:middle line:84%
think of "V for Vandetta," which
is another film that I think

00:43:15.070 --> 00:43:17.950 align:middle line:84%
deals with a lot of the
themes that we're discussing,

00:43:17.950 --> 00:43:20.700 align:middle line:84%
predictive
programming, dystopia.

00:43:20.700 --> 00:43:25.080 align:middle line:10%
And in "V for Vendetta," you
have a big landmark, Big Ben,

00:43:25.080 --> 00:43:27.300 align:middle line:10%
that's essentially destroyed.

00:43:27.300 --> 00:43:30.000 align:middle line:84%
In a lot of other
natural disaster movies,

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:33.870 align:middle line:84%
they love to destroy
the Golden Gate Bridge.

00:43:33.870 --> 00:43:37.020 align:middle line:84%
So I think that if we were to
pick out certain landmarks--

00:43:37.020 --> 00:43:38.520 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: That could
be the next one.

00:43:38.520 --> 00:43:39.900 align:middle line:90%
>>DYER: One one level--

00:43:39.900 --> 00:43:41.190 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: God, let's hope not.

00:43:41.190 --> 00:43:42.440 align:middle line:90%
>>DYER: But, yeah.

00:43:42.440 --> 00:43:45.240 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Jay, lot of competition
out there with everything.

00:43:45.240 --> 00:43:47.580 align:middle line:84%
You've got television,
you've got the internet,

00:43:47.580 --> 00:43:49.500 align:middle line:90%
you've got Facebook.

00:43:49.500 --> 00:43:51.180 align:middle line:84%
You've got all these
places coming up

00:43:51.180 --> 00:43:52.380 align:middle line:90%
with their own programming.

00:43:52.380 --> 00:43:54.142 align:middle line:90%
What's the future for films?

00:43:54.142 --> 00:43:55.850 align:middle line:84%
>>WEIDNER: That's a
really good question.

00:43:55.850 --> 00:43:57.610 align:middle line:90%
I think about that a lot.

00:43:57.610 --> 00:44:00.580 align:middle line:84%
I think that films
are losing some

00:44:00.580 --> 00:44:02.350 align:middle line:90%
of their sense of individuation.

00:44:02.350 --> 00:44:04.210 align:middle line:90%
I don't think there's really--

00:44:04.210 --> 00:44:07.450 align:middle line:84%
you can't really sense
a style from a director

00:44:07.450 --> 00:44:08.980 align:middle line:90%
as much as you used to.

00:44:08.980 --> 00:44:10.510 align:middle line:84%
Of course, people
like David Lynch,

00:44:10.510 --> 00:44:14.230 align:middle line:84%
you can see their style,
because it's so idiosyncratic.

00:44:14.230 --> 00:44:17.740 align:middle line:84%
But I think we're running
into kind of a sameness

00:44:17.740 --> 00:44:19.480 align:middle line:84%
now, in the way
that films are made,

00:44:19.480 --> 00:44:21.667 align:middle line:90%
and there's way too much CGI.

00:44:21.667 --> 00:44:24.250 align:middle line:84%
And I think that there's going
to be a rebellion against that.

00:44:24.250 --> 00:44:27.460 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to go down
to more base, good acting,

00:44:27.460 --> 00:44:30.410 align:middle line:84%
good writing kinds of films
are going to come back.

00:44:30.410 --> 00:44:32.259 align:middle line:84%
So it's really going
to be the creator.

00:44:32.259 --> 00:44:33.550 align:middle line:90%
It always has been the creator.

00:44:33.550 --> 00:44:35.480 align:middle line:90%
But Hollywood is losing control.

00:44:35.480 --> 00:44:36.570 align:middle line:90%
And that's a good thing.

00:44:36.570 --> 00:44:39.460 align:middle line:84%
Control is now coming back to
the independent film makers,

00:44:39.460 --> 00:44:42.550 align:middle line:84%
and the equipment and
technology is so low budget,

00:44:42.550 --> 00:44:45.220 align:middle line:84%
that a person with
not much money

00:44:45.220 --> 00:44:47.140 align:middle line:84%
can actually make an
interesting film now.

00:44:47.140 --> 00:44:49.450 align:middle line:84%
So I think the future's
very bright for the artist.

00:44:49.450 --> 00:44:51.700 align:middle line:84%
There's never been a
better time to be a content

00:44:51.700 --> 00:44:53.046 align:middle line:90%
creator than right now.

00:44:53.046 --> 00:44:54.670 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Your show,
"Hollywood Decoded"

00:44:54.670 --> 00:44:55.930 align:middle line:90%
is pretty cutting edge.

00:44:55.930 --> 00:44:58.897 align:middle line:84%
What can we expect
from you in the future?

00:44:58.897 --> 00:44:59.980 align:middle line:90%
>>DYER: More cutting edge.

00:44:59.980 --> 00:45:02.520 align:middle line:84%
In fact, we're going
to be taking apart

00:45:02.520 --> 00:45:04.530 align:middle line:84%
some of the biggest
films that are out there.

00:45:04.530 --> 00:45:05.904 align:middle line:84%
We're going to do
some Hitchcock.

00:45:05.904 --> 00:45:07.580 align:middle line:84%
We're going to do
more James Cameron.

00:45:07.580 --> 00:45:09.150 align:middle line:90%
We're going to do Ridley Scott.

00:45:09.150 --> 00:45:12.120 align:middle line:84%
We're going to do Christopher
Nolan films that run the gamut.

00:45:12.120 --> 00:45:14.481 align:middle line:90%
We've got "Batman," we've got--

00:45:14.481 --> 00:45:15.730 align:middle line:90%
>>WEIDNER: We've got them all.

00:45:15.730 --> 00:45:16.730 align:middle line:90%
>>DYER: We got them all.

00:45:16.730 --> 00:45:20.490 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I tell people not
everything's a conspiracy,

00:45:20.490 --> 00:45:23.790 align:middle line:84%
